      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i have a physics exam coming up and i'm struggling a bit with the concept of quantum entanglement. can you give me a concise, non-mathematical summary of what it actually is and how it's different from just regular classical correlation? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a bizarre, yet fundamental, concept where two or more particles become linked in such a way that they share the same fate, no matter how far apart they are. Imagine two of those linked particles, like two very peculiar, interconnected coins. If you measure a property of one particle—say, its spin—you instantly know the corresponding property of the other particle, even if it's across the galaxy. This is not like classical correlation, which is where the initial state is predetermined; with entanglement, the properties are genuinely undecided until the moment of measurement. The instantaneous connection is what baffled even Einstein, who famously called it \"spooky action at a distance.\"",
      "source": "target",
